observations.recommendation:
We reiterated our audit recommendations in CY 2022 and prior years with modification, that the Municipal Accountant:

Maintain a complete and updated PPE and Real Property Ledger Cards to ensure that all PPEs are properly accounted for and to easily facilitate the reconciliation of the RPCPPE with accounting records;

Trace back the transactions in the PPE balance labelled as unreconciled items from prior years (Table 1) to determine its nature and prepare the appropriate adjustments in the books of the Municipality;

Reclassify the incorrectly recorded PPEs to their proper account (Table 2, Table 3 and Table 4);

Reconcile the accounting records with the RPCPPE wherein differences noted should be verified and the corrections be made, where necessary; and

Determine the cost of the various donated equipment (Table 6) and recognize them as PPE in the books.

We also reiterated our previous recommendations, that the Municipal General Services Officer:

Assist the Municipal Accountant in determining the cost of the donated equipment and submit the related documents to the Municipal Accountant upon receipt, for proper recording; and

Ensure that Report of Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE) was prepared and accomplished completely when the physical count is concluded.

We recommended that Municipal Treasurer:

Obtain the Bank Statements of all the depository accounts of the LGU, especially from the Trust Fund accounts, and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant for the preparation of the Monthly Bank Reconciliation Statements;

Conduct the transfer of funds from Trust Fund to the General Fund for the total amount of taxes erroneously debited from the General Fund to be supported with a list of taxes withheld from Trust Fund projects; 

Henceforth, ensure that funds for the payment of of taxes withheld and other charges from other funds be transferred first to the General Fund prior to the utilization of the fund to avoid incurrence of negative Cash in Bank balances in the book of accounts; and

Strictly monitor the remittances of RPT dues to LGUs, both province and barangays, and reconcile first with the records of the Municipal Accountant, if necessary, to avoid incurrence of over/under remittances of tax dues

We also recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

Prepare the latest Bank Reconciliation Statement of all depository accounts of the LGU, especially those under the Trust Fund account, and submit the same to the Audit Team for auditing purposes;

Draw the adjusting entries to record the valid reconciling items and to restore the stale checks amounting ₱1,100,322.35 and ₱204,805.88, respectively; and 

Coordinate with the Municipal Treasurer in monitoring the remittances of taxes due and other charges to avoid incurrence of over/under remittances and prepare the necessary adjusting entries, if necessary, to avoid the reflecting negative balances of the Cash in Bank account in the book of accounts.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:

Ensure thru the Property/Supply Officer to accomplish the pre-repair inspection report after the conduct of pre-repair inspection of properties subjected for repairs. Likewise, when the subject properties were already repaired, conduct immediately post-repair inspection and submit a report thereon;

Direct the Property/Supply Officer to attach the Certificate of Acceptance and Report of Waste Material duly approved by the LCE after preliminary inspection/evaluation has been made;

Direct the GSO to ensure that the damaged/replaced, unserviceable supplies and property were kept in a safe stockroom located within the premises of the Municipality waiting for disposal thereof and disposed of in the manner prescribed by existing rules and regulations; and

Require the Municipal Accountant to see to it that all claims for repairs are supported with complete documentation to ensure that government funds are expended for proper and valid expenses as required under existing regulations.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant:

Submit documents such as RSMI with RIS and/or Distribution Sheets to substantiate the issuances/consumption/utilization of the Accountable Forms, Plate and Stickers, Food Supplies Inventory, Fuel Oil and Lubricant and Agricultural and Marine Supplies; 

Maintain Supplies Ledger Cards for every stock number and reconcile these with the Stock Cards of the GSO and the RPCI of the Inventory Committee.

We also recommended that the MGSO: 

Prepare and submit the SSMI duly supported with RIS weekly to the Accounting Office for recording of issuances of inventory items;

We further recommended that the Municipal Health Officer shall prepare a report on the issuances of Drugs and Medicines in the RHU per Fund Source and submit to the Municipal Accountant for recording in the books.

We reiterated our recommendations that the management:

Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to look into the details of the balances pertaining to fund transfers taken up as liability in the General Fund and Trust Fund books and take appropriate action such as submission of  liquidation  report to the source agency if needed, and facilitate the return of unspent balances to the source agency or remit to the Bureau of the Treasury or transfer to the General Fund of the Agency, whichever is applicable/appropriate, and immediately make the necessary adjustments in the books;

Direct the Municipal Planning and Development Office to coordinate with and assist the OIC-Municipal Accountant in verifying whether the projects/programs associated with the funds received were already implemented and to secure the necessary documents in order to facilitate the liquidation to source agency, if needed, and in the recording of adjustments in the books; 

Ensure that there is proper coordination between the Municipal Accounting Office and the Municipal Planning and Development Office to avoid recurring the noted observation in any future undertakings the agency may accept, especially fund transfers from NGAs.

We reiterated our recommendations that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
Issue demand letters to notify the concerned officials and employees of their responsibility to settle their unliquidated cash advances. If settlement was not received, withhold from their salaries considering that they have been notified and given more adequate time to liquidate;
Issue demand letters to employees who already resigned and transferred to immediately cause the liquidation or settlement of the unliquidated balances;
Request the write-off of the unliquidated cash advances balance of the deceased employees;
Not grant additional cash advance to concerned officials and employees unless the previous cash advance granted them have been liquidated; and
Strictly monitor periodically the submission of liquidation reports to ensure timely accounting thereof to avoid undue accumulation of outstanding cash advances.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Disbursing Officers to immediately submit the liquidation reports in order to preclude the issuance of the Notice of Suspension as may be warranted;
The Accounting Office exert efforts to locate the required documents to make the necessary adjustments for the unrecorded liquidations if there’s any;
The Municipal Accountant provide the schedule of the Advances for Payroll account for easy determination of the unliquidated balances; and
Stop the practice of granting additional cash advance to DO if the previous cash advance is not yet liquidated.

We reiterated the following recommendations to Management:
The Local Chief Executive create an Inventory Committee to perform the annual physical count of PPE and inventory;
Reconcile the results of the count with the accounting records and submit the complete and accurate RPCPPE to the Audit Team, pursuant to Section 124 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Volume 1;
After reconciliation, management should consider disposing the unserviceable, request from COA for the derecognition of non-existing and missing PPEs from the Agency’s book of accounts, in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, otherwise known as the Guidelines and Procedures in the Conduct of Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (PPE), Recognition of PPE Items Found at Station, and Disposition for Non-existing/Missing PPE Items, for the One-Time Cleansing of PPE Account Balances of Government Agencies;
The Municipal Accountant to start keeping Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards for each category of assets; and Real Property Ledger Cards for land; and
The Municipal Treasurer to start maintaining Property Cards per category of property, plant and equipment.

We reiterated our prior year’s audit recommendations, with modifications, that the Municipal Accountant:
Ensure the maintenance of complete and updated PPE and Real Property Ledger Cards to ensure proper accounting of all PPEs and to facilitate the efficient reconciliation of the RPCPPE with accounting records;
Trace the transactions comprising the unreconciled items from prior years (Table 1) to determine their nature and prepare the necessary adjusting entries in the municipality’s books;
Reclassify the incorrectly recorded PPEs (Table 2 and 3) to their appropriate asset accounts;
Conduct a thorough reconciliation of the accounting records with the RPCPPE. Any discrepancies identified should be verified, and corresponding corrections should be made where necessary; and
Prepare a journal entry voucher to record the various donated equipment (Table 5) and corresponding depreciation expenses in the books.
We also recommended that the Municipal General Services Officer ensure that the Report of Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE) is accomplished completely to enable faster reconciliation of PPE accounts upon completion of the physical count.

We recommended that the Mayor, as Chairman of the Municipal Development Council, and the Municipal Planning and Development Officer:
Submit a written justification for the implementation of the noted projects in Table 20 despite their non-inclusion in the approved AIP;
Conduct detailed engineering of all projects, with the assistance of the Municipal Engineer, prior to its inclusion in the AIP which includes the preparation of the Program of Work with the Detailed Estimates and plans/specifications to facilitate thorough planning and monitoring of the projects’ implementation;
Ensure that all PPAs implemented are included in the approved Annual Investment Plan of the municipality; and
Stop utilizing the 20% Development Fund for expenditures that are expressly not allowed in Section 3.2.5 of DBM-DOF-DILG JMC No. 2020-1.

We recommended that the MDRRM Officer and Municipal Budget Officer:
utilize the LDRRM Fund, especially those in the Special Trust Fund, for programs, projects, and activities that align with the approved LDRRMF Investment Plan. This ensures well-planned and MDRRM Council-authorized fund utilization;
verify the accuracy of fund charging to ensure that expenditures designated for the STF are correctly obligated, in accordance with the approved budget and LDRRMF Investment Plan;
clearly define all PPAs by specifying their titles and estimated costs to facilitate effective monitoring and evaluation. Additionally, provide a detailed budget breakdown for each project or activity to enhance transparency and ensure efficient fund utilization; and
conduct a thorough review of the existing budget allocations and expenditure classifications to ensure that future expenses are properly categorized, thereby preventing misclassification.

3.21 	Recommendations:
We recommended and the Management agreed that the:
Inventory and Disposal Committee conduct physical count of inventory items by type on a semestral basis and report the same in the Report of the Physical Count of Inventories which shall be submitted to the Audit Team not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively;
Municipal Treasurer take custody of all supplies and materials received and control their release through the use of the Requisition and Issue Slip (RIS);
Municipal Treasurer consolidate weekly the RIS for all issued supplies using the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI); and submit the same, along with the original RIS, to the Municipal Accountant on a weekly basis;
Municipal Accountant record the utilized inventories based on the SSMI, as supported by the weekly RIS, on a weekly basis;
Municipal Accountant record the P521,284.00 construction materials already utilized to the Construction in Progress-Infrastructure Asset account, copy furnished the Audit Team; and
Municipal Accountant reconcile the balance as of December 31, 2024 of the Other Supplies and Materials Inventory account with the balance per stock cards, and effect the necessary adjusting entries to correct the inventory balance, copy furnished the Audit Team.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor and government officials and employees concerned:

Submit the lacking supporting documents noted in Appendix D.8 to avoid suspension in audit; 

Refund the excess amount of Daily Travel Expense claimed for their respective travels totaling ₱215,518.37 (Appendix D.9);

Henceforth, only approve travels to the most necessary and essential to the effective performance of an official or employee’s mandates and functions.

We also recommended management to stop granting travel allowances beyond what is allowed under Executive Order No. 77, to avoid incurrence of irregular expenditures and disallowances in audit.

We recommended that the management direct the following personnel;

The HRMO to (a) prepare a contract instead of an office order to serve as a basis for the hiring of personnel on a Job Order basis and (b) furnish a copy of the contracts, Accomplishment Reports and DTRs of the JOs the personnel/office who is processing the payroll for payment of their salary; and 

The Municipal Accountant to: a) submit the required supporting documents, and :b) make sure that all supporting documents for all disbursements made are complete to preclude the issuance of audit suspension or disallowance.

We recommend that the Local Chief Executive:

 (a) require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to trace the material variance of ₱22,662,054.80 for Cash in Bank Account and ₱23,730.11 for Cash in Local Treasury Account as of December 31, 2019;

(b) require henceforth, reconciliation of entries in the cashbook and general ledger at least on a quarterly basis and promptly resolve any significant discrepancy accordingly.

Should intensify their collections and reduce as much as possible their expenditures so that risk of unhealthy financial position can be addressed;

Require the Local Chief Executive to initiate the review of operations of the Market as an economic enterprise.

Conduct periodic and continuous monitoring and review of the implementation of strategies with the end view that the desired results are achieved.

We reiterated our audit recommendations in CY 2022 and prior years with modification, that the Municipal Accountant:
a. Maintain a complete and updated PPE and Real Property Ledger Cards to ensure that all PPEs are properly accounted for and to easily facilitate the reconciliation of the RPCPPE with accounting records;
b. Trace back the transactions in the PPE balance labelled as unreconciled items from prior years to determine its nature and prepare the appropriate adjustments in the books of the Municipality;
c. Reclassify the incorrectly recorded PPEs to their proper account;
d. Reconcile the accounting records with the RPCPPE wherein differences noted should be verified and the corrections be made, where necessary; and
e. Determine the cost of the various donated equipment and recognize them as PPE in the books.

We also reiterated our previous recommendations, that the Municipal General Services Officer:
a. Assist the Municipal Accountant in determining the cost of the donated equipment and submit the related documents to the Municipal Accountant upon receipt, for proper recording; and
b. Ensure that Report of Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE) was prepared and accomplished completely when the physical count is concluded.

We reiterated our recommendation that management:

1.	Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to look into the details of the balances pertaining to fund transfers taken up as liability in the General Fund and Trust Fund books and take appropriate action such as submission of  liquidation  report to the source agency if needed and facilitate the return of unspent balances to the source agency or remit to the Bureau of the Treasury or transfer to the General Fund of the Agency, whichever is applicable/appropriate, and to make the necessary adjustments in the books immediately;

2.	Direct the Municipal Planning and Development Office to coordinate with and assist the OIC-Municipal Accountant in verifying whether the projects/programs associated with the funds received were already implemented and to secure the necessary documents in order to facilitate the liquidation to source agency, if needed, and in the recording of adjustments in the books; 

3.	Ensure that proper coordination between the Municipal Accounting Office and the Municipal Planning and Development Office must be had to avoid recurring the noted observation in any future undertakings the agency may accept, especially fund transfers from NGAs.

We recommended Management to:

Enforce the immediate liquidation and/or settlement of all outstanding cash advances;

Stop the practice of granting additional cash advances to officials/employees who have previous unliquidated cash advances as well as granting multiple cash advances to the same employees regardless of the purpose;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to expedite the request for the write-off of long outstanding cash advances that are considered dormant following the guidelines and procedures provided in COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016; and

Strictly adhere to the guidelines outlined in COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997, in the granting and liquidation of cash advances.

We recommended that the MACCO and Property Officer (Municipal Treasurer): 

1.  Follow the procedures, prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers and property records, and create a mechanism that the amounts in RPCPPE and PPE in the books of accounts are reconciled at year-end;

2.  Ensure that the accounts used per RPCPPE and SLs are similar to facilitate easy reconciliation and submit a reconciliation of the reported differences.

We recommended that management require the Municipal Accountant to
Issue demand letters to notify the concerned officials and employees of their responsibility to settle their unliquidated cash advances. If settlement was not received, withhold from their salaries considering that they have been notified and given more adequate time to liquidate;
Issue demand letters to employees who already resigned and transferred to immediately cause the liquidation or settlement of the unliquidated balances;
Request the write-off of the unliquidated cash advances balance of the deceased employees;
Ensure the completeness of prescribed supporting documents for the granting of cash advances in processing claims for payment thereof;
Not grant additional cash advance to concerned officials and employees unless the previous cash advance granted them have been liquidated; and
Strictly monitor periodically the submission of liquidation reports to ensure timely accounting thereof to avoid undue accumulation of outstanding cash advances.

Based on the foregoing circumstances, we recommended the management to:
Require the Accounting Office, in coordination with the Implementing Office (DSWD), to liquidate the long-outstanding fund transfer;
Henceforth, return to the Source Agency any unused/unutilized balance relating to the fund transfers;
Explain the cause of delayed liquidation of fund transfers; and

We recommended that:
Management submits all lacking documents for audit purposes;
Management limits the practice of serving meals and snacks during meetings particularly those events which are considered among the regular or normal activities of the municipality;
Management observes austerity measures when serving meals and snacks during meetings;
The Municipal Mayor, as head of the local government unit, safeguard the municipality’s funds and resources by exercising prudence in utilization thereof;
Henceforth, all disbursements for meals and snacks served during seminars/orientation/training should be supported by complete, sufficient and relevant documents to establish the validity of the claim; and
Management strictly complies with the above-mentioned provisions.

We recommended the following courses of action:
1. Secure the approval of the Sangguniang Bayan through a resolution authorizing the Municipal Mayor to execute a Deed of Donation or Memorandum of Agreement to transfer PPEs processed and used by other agencies;
2. The OIC - Municipal Accountant shall make the necessary adjusting entries to derecognize from the books of the agency the PPE items that will be transferred to other agencies and to adjust the erroneous entries made on PPE and depreciation accounts;
3. Ensure the full implementation of the “One-time cleansing of PPE accounts” and undertake all procedures as provided for in COA Circular 2020-006 to come up with reconciled and correct balances of PPE accounts in the financial statements.

We reiterated our recommendation that management:
1. Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to look into the details of the balances pertaining to fund transfers taken up as liability in the General Fund and Trust Fund books and take appropriate action such as submission of liquidation report to the source agency if needed and facilitate the return of unspent balances to the source agency or remit to the Bureau of the Treasury or transfer to the General Fund of the Agency, whichever is applicable/appropriate, and to make the necessary adjustments in the books immediately;
2. Direct the Municipal Planning and Development Office to coordinate with and assist the OIC-Municipal Accountant in verifying whether the projects/programs associated with the funds received were already implemented and to secure the necessary documents in order to facilitate the liquidation to source agency, if needed, and in the recording of adjustments in the books; 
3. Ensure that proper coordination between the Municipal Accounting Office and the Municipal Planning and Development Office must be had to avoid recurring the noted observation in any future undertakings the agency may accept, especially fund transfers from NGAs.

We recommended Management to:
Enforce the immediate liquidation and/or settlement of all outstanding cash advances;
Stop the practice of granting additional cash advances to officials/employees who have previous unliquidated cash advances as well as granting multiple cash advances to the same employees regardless of the purpose;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to expedite the request for the write-off of long outstanding cash advances that are considered dormant following the guidelines and procedures provided in COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016; and
Strictly adhere to the guidelines outlined in COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997, in the granting and liquidation of cash advances.

Require the Municipal Mayor to create an Inventory Committee who will conduct physical inventory of all its Property, Plant and Equipment together with the General Services Office (MGSO)/ Municipal Treasurer on a specific time table;
Monitor submission of the Report on the Physical count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE); and
Require the Municipal Accountant to periodically reconcile recorded entries in the PPE account with the RPCPPE and property cards for an immediate adjustment in either books/records.

Recommendations:
We recommended and the Management agreed to the following courses of action for the Municipal Mayor:
To instruct the Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count earlier to give enough time for the preparation and submission of the RPCPPE on or before the prescribed deadline;
Enjoin the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to undertake collaborative efforts to immediately reconcile the RPCPPE with the accounting records, following the procedures enumerated under Items 6.3.1 and 6.3.2 of COA Circular No. 2020-006;
To avail of the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts under COA Circular 2020-006 for the disposition of non-existing/missing/unserviceable PPE items to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition, and accountability;
To instruct the Municipal Treasurer to immediately facilitate the transfer of the above PPEs covered with the SB resolution to their respective users, and to furnish the Municipal Accountant a copy of such documents for proper recording; and
To secure an authority from the Sangguniang Bayan by way of resolution to authorize the Municipal Mayor to execute a Deed of Donation (DOD) or a Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) for the remaining properties not covered by SB Reso. No. 2022-230.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the 

(a) Market Administrator to 

(i) ensure that all stall occupancy is governed by valid contracts; 

(ii) initiate extra efforts to update the collection reports in order to facilitate collection of unpaid rentals, and impose necessary penalties on delayed payments, as the case maybe; and 

(iii) prepare monthly status report of collection to determine if target collections is met; and 

(b) Municipal Accountant to 

(i) create and update subsidiary ledgers to monitor payment of rental of each stallholder; 

(ii) maintain the Special Accounts for market operations in the General Fund; 

(iii) prepare the corresponding schedules to support the market’s financial statements which will serve as tools in informing Management for evaluation and decision-making purposes; and 

(iv) recognize in the books the receivables from accrued rental fees from the market.

We recommended that Management:

1.	Direct the Municipal Treasurer to exert more effort to expedite the collection of taxes due and collectible by sending demand letters to delinquent taxpayers giving priority to delinquent taxpayers having large balances, and;

2.	Avail of the remedies provided for by law to enforce the strict and prompt collection of delinquent real property taxes.

Require the Municipal Mayor to create an Inventory Committee who will conduct physical inventory of all its Property, Plant and Equipment together with the General Services Office (MGSO)/ Municipal Treasurer on a specific time table;

Monitor submission of the Report on the Physical count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE); and

Require the Municipal Accountant to periodically reconcile recorded entries in the PPE account with the RPCPPE and property cards for an immediate adjustment in either books/records.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor enjoin the:

a. Municipal Engineer to submit monthly, aside from the list of building permits issued, the list of persons/establishments issued with certificates of occupancy/installation for assessment purposes, and;

b. Municipal Assessor to conduct inspection and assessment within a reasonable period of time. And, submit to MEO list of real properties found during its ocular inspections without corresponding building and/or occupancy permits.

We recommended that management:

1. Stop the practice of assigning job order personnel to collect revenues;

2. If warranted by funds, consider the regularization of the job order personnel so as they can perform collection functions.

We recommended that the MACCO and Property Officer (Municipal Treasurer): 

1.  Follow the procedures, prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers and property records, and create a mechanism that the amounts in RPCPPE and PPE in the books of accounts are reconciled at year-end; 

2.  Ensure that the accounts used per RPCPPE and SLs are similar to facilitate easy reconciliation and submit a reconciliation of the reported differences; 

3. Secure records/documents pertaining to the amount of P349,083.63 motorcycles transferred without cost and draw appropriate entry/ies to record the same in the municipality’s books.

We recommended that management:

1.	Stop the practice of assigning job order personnel to collect revenues;

If warranted by funds, consider the regularization of the job order personnel so as they can perform collection functions.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Treasurer to:

Enjoin the AOs to manually prepare and submit timely their Monthly RAAF;

Designate regular personnel who shall initially review and verify the RAAFs submitted by the AOs;

Prepare monthly the CRAAF and submit it together with the RAAFs of the AOs within the prescribed period; and

Make representation with the ETRACS developer to ascertain the cause/s of the error and to develop ways to resolve such error.

Require the Municipal Mayor to create an Inventory Committee who will conduct physical inventory of all its Property, Plant and Equipment together with the General Services Office (MGSO)/ Municipal Treasurer on a specific time table;

Require the MGSO/ Municipal Treasurer to prepare Property Cards on all counted items and on all subsequent acquisition/ procurements for the year;

Monitor submission of the Report on the Physical count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE); and

Require the Municipal Accountant to periodically reconcile recorded entries in the PPE account with the RPCPPE and property cards for an immediate adjustment in either books/records.

The MGSO/Municipal Treasurer should annually plan and prepare schedule in the conduct of physical inventory and the preparation of the corresponding RPCPPE for its timely submission on or before January 31 of each year.

We recommended that the MACCO and Property Officer (Municipal Treasurer): 

1.  Follow the procedures, prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers and property records, and create a mechanism that the amounts in RPCPPE and PPE in the books of accounts are reconciled at year-end; 

2.  Ensure that the accounts used per RPCPPE and SLs are similar to facilitate easy reconciliation and submit a reconciliation of the reported differences; 

3. Secure records/documents pertaining to the amount of P349,083.63 motorcycles transferred without cost and draw appropriate entry/ies to record the same in the municipality’s books.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the BAC Chairman, persons authorized to conduct Shopping/Small Value Procurement by the BAC and acceptance and inspection committee to undertake the following courses of actions in order to strengthen the internal control system of the LGU particularly on the preparation and execution of procurement documents: 
1. Ensure that every PO be duly filled up with the data needed as guide for the suppliers in complying with the terms and conditions of the contract and as guide for the LGU in the imposition of sanctions, if needed. Data such as the date of signing of PO by the supplier and full name and signature of the representative of the supplier must be indicated in the conforme section; 

2. The supply/property division/ BAC shall assigned the PO numbers for all POs issued and entered into by the LGU, for control purposes and easy monitoring; 

3. Ensure that the actual date of the acceptance and inspection of the items/goods procured as well as whether or not these are completely/partially delivered must be indicated. These data are required in order to have sufficient basis to demand from the supplier liquidated damages or penalty of  1/10 of 1% of the cost of undelivered items per day of delay, in case of the latter’s failure to meet the contract time/period; and 
4. Ensure that the RFQ is in prescribe the manner by which price quotations shall be submitted i.e., by sealed or open quotation, and the deadline for their submission. The ABC must be indicated and the price quoted by the supplier must be indicated as these data are required for examination, evaluation, and comparison and preparation of Abstract of Quotations.

We reiterated our previous audit recommendations that the Municipal Mayor:

Enjoins the MBO and the Municipal Engineer to fast track the implementation/completion of projects from prior and current year; and;

2.	Further, we recommended that the Local Development Council should optimize the utilization of the 20% Development Fund through: (a) proper planning of project including timing of execution; (b) coordinated action from LGU officials for better result and (c) strict monitoring in project implementation to ensure accomplishment of the project.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the (a) Sangguniang Bayan, OIC-Municipal Accountant, Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer (MDRRMO) and BAC Chairman to 

write explanation on the failure of the agency to revise the LDRRMFIP and APP to incorporate the expenses related to address the COVID-19 pandemic;

(ii) submit the required documents immediately to the Office of the Auditor for further review/evaluation of the transactions pursuant to Section 4(6) of Presidential Decree No. 1445 and in compliance with the required reportorial requirements of GPPB Circular 2020-001;

(b) Human Resources and Management Officer to review and verify the submitted DTRs and forwards the same to the Accounting Office for preparation of payrolls; and

(c) OIC-Municipal Accountant to 

(i) prepare the payrolls based on the submitted Daily Time Records (DTRs) to avoid overpayment

(ii) comply with the accounting and reporting guidelines on the receipt and utilization of LDRRMF to present fairly the expense and inventory accounts in the Financial Statements pursuant to COA Circular No. 2014-002 dated April 15, 2014 and COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015;

(iii) ensure that all the disbursements are supported with complete documents before making the payment; and

(iv) ensure that all the supporting documents are properly signed and the necessary information in various forms are properly and completely filled-up.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the 

Officer-in -charge to stop the practice of granting fuels to be used by private vehicles;



(b) OIC-Municipal Budget Officer meticulously check the available appropriation/budget for a particular disbursement before charging it against the fund;

(c) OIC-Municipal Accountant to 

(i) present the expense accounts in the financial statements based on the nature of expense;



(ii) ensure that all the disbursements are supported with complete required documents before making the payment; and

(iii) submit the lacking documentary requirements pertaining to the transactions.

We recommended that management:

Adequately plan and thoroughly study the feasibility of each project before proposing it to be included as one of the projects to be funded by the 20% LGDF;

Ensure proper coordination among concerned offices;

Ensure immediate action and exert additional effort for the timely implementation of the projects; and

Ensure the full utilization of the appropriated amounts for the benefit of the constituents in terms of PPAs to be implemented under 20% LGDF.

We recommend that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Treasurer to:

Update the balances in the ledger to reflect whether there have been unrecorded disbursements pertaining to each individual water system projects and if there is none;

To either return the unutilized balance of P1,487,627.00 to the source agency or deposit the amount to the National Treasury.

We reiterated our recommendations that Management:
explain and/or justify the incurrence of cash deficit/overdraft in the Trust - Proper account;
refrain from using trust fund money for purposes other than those for which the trust was created or the funds received pursuant to Section 305 (e) of RA 7160;
ensure that trust obligations have sufficient cash back-up.

We recommended that management require the Municipal Accountant to:
continue issuing demand letters to concerned officials and employees of their responsibility to settle their unliquidated cash advances. If settlement was not received, withhold from their salaries any unliquidated cash advances, considering that they have been notified and given adequate time to liquidate;
exert extra effort to issue demand letters to employees and officials who are no longer connected with the LGU to immediately cause the liquidation or settlement of the unliquidated balances;
also, continue not to grant additional cash advances to individuals with existing balance; and
Strictly comply with the provisions of the abovementioned Circulars.

We recommended that management:
reclassify the account Other Prepayment to Advances to Contractors for fair presentation of the accounts;
trace-back all available records pertaining to the cancelled project;
demand the immediate refund of the remaining unrecouped advances from the contractor; and
exert all effort to recoup advance payments to prevent loss of government fund.

We recommended that management:
Explain the reason of the delay/non-implementation of the projects stated above;
Conduct an inventory of work accomplished by the contractor and impose liquidated damages at least equal to one-tenth of one percent (0.1%) of the cost of the unperformed portion for every day of delay;
Carry out detailed engineering to ensure issues such as encroachment of private property and project viability are properly addressed during the feasibility or preliminary engineering studies; and
Intensify monitoring of project in order to avoid recurrence of delay to other projects.

We recommended the management to:
submit explanation why the LGU did not obtain immediately the details and signature of the beneficiaries upon distribution of the biological asset;
submit the complete list of beneficiaries of the goat dispersal program;
submit the project proposal; and
execute a written contract between the municipality and the beneficiaries stating the terms and conditions and copy furnished the audit team.

Based on the foregoing circumstances, we reiterated our recommendations that management:
Require the Municipal Accountant to update, reconcile and revisit the balances reported with the source agency immediately and draw adjusting ectries as necessary;
Require the Accountable Officer of the said fund transfers to review the implementation of the same and cause the liquidation thereof;
Return to the Source Agency any unused/unutilized balance relating to the fund transfers; and
Explain the cause of delayed liquidation of fund transfers.

We recommended Management:
